                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Office of<lb/></p>
            <p>ARTHUR SCHWARTZ&#44;<lb/>
                SUCCESSOR TO J. B. DANIEL&#44;<lb/>
                DRUGGSIT AND APOTHECARY<lb/>
                &#45;&#45;AND DEALER IN&#45;&#45;<lb/>
                PAINTS&#44; OILS&#44; GLASS&#44; PUTTY&#44; FLAVORING EXTRACTS AND ESSENCES&#44;<lb/>
                DRUGGISTS&#39; FANCY GOODS&#44; ETC.<lb/>
                ALSO&#44; MANUFACTURERS OF<lb/>
                AMERICAN SPECIFIC&#44; ELYSIAN LUNG ELIXER AND BROMO COMPOUND.<lb/>
                S. E. Corner Centre and Bridge Streets&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Trenton&#44; N. J.&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;188<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev&#58; S Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>My Dear Sir.<lb/></p>
            <p>I take the privilege by addressing<lb/> to you a few lines&#44; which I hope<lb/> will be available to your kind<lb/> consideration.  Looking <sic>ove</sic> The<lb/> &#34;Philad<hi rend="sup">a</hi> Times&#34; of this mornings issue<lb/> I was once more surprised with the tidings of our<lb/> race from <sic>Roumenia</sic>&#44; it is simply a<lb/> calamity which needs no repetition&#44; as<lb/> we have known the <sic>evel</sic> in years gone<lb/> by.  The <sic>evel</sic> is an existing monster<lb/> which cannot be evaded by our govern&#45;<lb/>ment&#44; or monarchical interferences&#44; it<lb/> has been lived and most signally failed&#44;<lb/> and now it is more than a cloud in the<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>eyes of our race&#44; or at least in the<lb/> eyes of those who have a drop of the<lb/> Israelite blood&#44; or the least&#45;claim of brotherhood&#44;<lb/> it remains for us to share our sympathy&#44;<lb/> to encourage and concentrate our<lb/> people to direct a momentous<lb/> attention in their behalf before<lb/> it is too late&#44; the emigration is not at<lb/> all impossible&#44; and we should re&#45;<lb/>ceive the sufferers with more than<lb/> ordinary attention.  The far west is a vast<lb/> &#38; beautiful country&#44; &#38; I believe our<lb/> <sic>Amerikan</sic> people will receive them with <del>as<lb/> much&#44;</del> equal protection.  I am very much<lb/> interested &#38; have been during the Russo&#45;Turkish<lb/> complication in their behalf.  I openly<lb/> boast that our people in the City of Trenton<lb/> will be amongst the first who will <sic>annswer</sic><lb/> to their cause.  Let not thy exertion rest&#44;<lb/> but let thy future be crowned with charity.<lb/></p>
            <p>I remain Yours fraternally<lb/> A. Schwartz<lb/></p>
            </body>
